Structure data for LM

Normalize function

normalize <- function(x) {
    return ((x - mean(x)) / sd(x))
  }

filter and normalize df

LMdf <- df %>% 
  mutate(sqrt_shrubarea3 = sqrt(shrubarea3)) %>%
  mutate(log_shrubarea3 = log(shrubarea3+1)) %>%
  dplyr::select(Fire, 
         Sdlg, 
         VertGrowth_Rel, 
         Years, 
         Ht_cm1, 
         sqrt_shrubarea3, 
         log_shrubarea3, 
         BasDia2016.cm, 
         incidrad, 
         Year, 
         Elevation, 
         siteclass,
         heatload, 
         ShrubSpp03) %>% 
 mutate_if(is.numeric, normalize) %>% 
  mutate(VertGrowth_Rel = df$VertGrowth_Rel)
LMdf <- droplevels(LMdf)

Model using VSURF var results

Convert vars to formula structure

vars_one <- paste(vars, collapse = " + ")
vars_one
## [1] "Ht_cm1 + Years + sqrt_shrubarea3 + heatload + ShrubSpp03 + BasDia2016.cm + Year"
f <- formula(paste("VertGrowth_Rel ~ ",vars_one))
f
## VertGrowth_Rel ~ Ht_cm1 + Years + sqrt_shrubarea3 + heatload + 
##     ShrubSpp03 + BasDia2016.cm + Year

Run lme model

LM <- lme(f, data = LMdf, random = ~ 1| Fire/Sdlg, method = "ML")

See whether model with or without interaction is better

vars_int <- paste(vars_one, "+ Ht_cm1:sqrt_shrubarea3")
f_int <- formula(paste("VertGrowth_Rel ~ ",vars_int))
LM_int <- lme(f_int, data = LMdf, random = ~ 1| Fire/Sdlg, method = "ML")
AIC(LM)
## [1] 360.8311
AIC(LM_int)
## [1] 356.3178
if(
  AIC(LM) > AIC(LM_int)
) print(paste("WITH INTERACTION WINS BY", round(AIC(LM)-AIC(LM_int), digits = 2), "AIC")) else print(paste("WITHOUT INTERACTION WINS BY", round(AIC(LM_int)-AIC(LM), digits = 2)))
## [1] "WITH INTERACTION WINS BY 4.51 AIC"

Run anova by hand for the interacting variables since drop1 doesn’t do that by default

vars_no_shrub <- str_replace(vars_one, "sqrt_shrubarea3 +", "")
vars_no_shrub
## [1] "Ht_cm1 + Years + + heatload + ShrubSpp03 + BasDia2016.cm + Year"
f_no_shrub <- formula(paste("VertGrowth_Rel ~ ", vars_no_shrub))
LM_noshrub <- lme(f_no_shrub, data = LMdf, random = ~ 1| Fire/Sdlg, method = "ML")
anova(LM_int, LM_noshrub)
##            Model df      AIC      BIC    logLik   Test L.Ratio p-value
## LM_int         1 17 356.3178 416.2505 -161.1589                       
## LM_noshrub     2 15 376.5938 429.4756 -173.2969 1 vs 2  24.276  <.0001
vars_no_ht <- vars[vars != "Ht_cm1"]
vars_no_ht_one <- paste(vars_no_ht, collapse = " + ")
f_no_ht <- formula(paste("VertGrowth_Rel ~ ", vars_no_ht_one))
LM_noht <- lme(f_no_ht, data = LMdf, random = ~ 1| Fire/Sdlg, method = "ML")
anova(LM_int, LM_noht)

Look at individual effects

Note: the plots look exactly the same but with different axes if you don’t normalize the numeric predictors. So for including plots to visualize in the paper, I just use non-normalized data

plot(predictorEffect("Years", LM))

plot(predictorEffect("sqrt_shrubarea3", LM))

plot(predictorEffect("Ht_cm1", LM))

plot(predictorEffect("ShrubSpp03", LM))

Create df for effects and confidence intervals using mean +/- 1 SD

quartiles <- summary(df$Ht_cm1)[c(2,5)]
quartiles <- (quartiles-mean(df$Ht_cm1))/sd(df$Ht_cm1)
eff_shrubarea <- predictorEffect("sqrt_shrubarea3", LM_int, xlevels = list(Ht_cm1 = quartiles))
effects_df <- as.data.frame(eff_shrubarea)

Transform variables back to original units

effects_df <- effects_df %>% 
  mutate(sqrt_shrubarea3 = sqrt_shrubarea3*sd(sqrt(df$shrubarea3))+mean(sqrt(df$shrubarea3)) ) %>% 
  mutate(Ht_cm1 = Ht_cm1*sd(df$Ht_cm1)+mean(df$Ht_cm1) ) %>% 
  mutate(Ht_cm1 = as.factor(round(Ht_cm1)) )

Plot effects of shrubarea WITH interaction

ggplot(effects_df)+
  geom_line(aes(x = sqrt_shrubarea3, y = exp(fit), group = Ht_cm1, col = Ht_cm1))+
  geom_ribbon(aes(x = sqrt_shrubarea3, ymin = exp(lower), ymax = exp(upper), group = Ht_cm1, fill = Ht_cm1), alpha = .5)+

  ylab("Relative growth rate")+

Find the shrubarea values associated with each quartile, and the mean growth for each of those

summary <- summary(sqrt(df$shrubarea3))
summary
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   57.45  190.79  264.95  269.17  342.05  501.80
quart1 <- summary[2]
quart3 <- summary[5]
median <- summary[3]
min <- summary[1]
max <- summary[6]
mean <- mean(sqrt(df$shrubarea3))

fit_quart1 <- effects_df[which.min(abs(effects_df$sqrt_shrubarea3 - quart1)),]$fit
fit_quart1
## [1] -1.619568
fit_quart3 <- effects_df[which.min(abs(effects_df$sqrt_shrubarea3 - quart3)),]$fit
fit_median <- effects_df[which.min(abs(effects_df$sqrt_shrubarea3 - median)),]$fit
fit_min <- effects_df[which.min(abs(effects_df$sqrt_shrubarea3 - min)),]$fit
fit_max <- effects_df[which.min(abs(effects_df$sqrt_shrubarea3 - max)),]$fit
fit_mean <- effects_df[which.min(abs(effects_df$sqrt_shrubarea3 - mean)),]$fit
mean <- mean(df$shrubarea3/10000)
